ğŸ”¹ What is Set?

Set is an interface in Java (part of Collection Framework).

It does not allow duplicate elements.

It stores only unique elements.

Syntax:
Set<Integer> st = new HashSet<>();
// or
Set<Integer> st = new LinkedHashSet<>();
// or
Set<Integer> st = new TreeSet<>();

ğŸ”¹ Why do we use Set?

By using Set, we can:

âœ… Find unique elements

ğŸ” Search elements efficiently

âŒ Remove duplicates automatically

ğŸ”¢ Sort elements (using TreeSet)

ğŸ‘‰ This line is very important for your mind map.

ğŸ“Œ Types of Set
1ï¸âƒ£ HashSet
ğŸ”¹ Properties:

Does NOT follow any order

Stores elements based on hashing

Fastest among all Set implementations

ğŸ”¹ Time Complexity:

add() â†’ O(1) (average)

contains() â†’ O(1)

remove() â†’ O(1)

ğŸ”¹ Important Points:

Order is random

Allows only one null value

Best when order doesnâ€™t matter

2ï¸âƒ£ LinkedHashSet
ğŸ”¹ Properties:

Maintains insertion order

Internally implemented using:

Hash table + Doubly Linked List

ğŸ”¹ Time Complexity:

add() â†’ O(1)

contains() â†’ O(1)

remove() â†’ O(1)

ğŸ”¹ Important Points:

Slightly slower than HashSet

Used when order of input matters

3ï¸âƒ£ TreeSet
ğŸ”¹ Properties:

Stores elements in sorted order (Ascending)

Internally implemented as:

Balanced BST (Red-Black Tree)

ğŸ”¹ Time Complexity:

add() â†’ O(log n)

contains() â†’ O(log n)

remove() â†’ O(log n)

ğŸ”¹ Important Points:

Does NOT allow null values

Used when sorting is required

